AGI - Start tomorrow, March 3, the State visit of the President of the Republic Sergio&nbsp;Mattarella&nbsp; in the Country of the Levant, where a busy agenda of institutional commitments awaits him: in the Capital, Tokyo, until March 6 and, subsequently, in Kyoto and Hiroshima, before returning to Rome, March 10. The program includes a meeting, already in the evening of Monday, with the Italian community of Tokyo, while the day of March 4 will be dominated by the institutional commitments starting from the visit to the Imperial Palace, where&nbsp;Mattarella&nbsp; will meet the rulers of the throne of the chrysanthemum, Emperor Naruhito and Empress Masako>. In the afternoon the head of the state will instead be at the National Diet for talks with the presidents of the two rooms. On March 5, &nbsp;Mattarella&nbsp;will visit the headquarters of Keidanren, the Japanese Confindustria, for a meeting with important representatives of the economy and entrepreneurship of the two countries, an event that will prepare the important Italian-Japanese business forum of May 13 in Rome.
It is not planned to sign other protocols after those signed in 2023 to promote bilateral economic, industrial and technological cooperation, but the stage, followed by the bilateral afternoon with Prime Minister Shigeru Ishiba, will be expected to strengthen the strategic partnership between two countries with common challenges (among all demographic and environmental challenges) and equally threatened by the American protectionist policy inaugurated by Trump. The mission of&nbsp;Mattarella&nbsp; will continue between Kyoto and Hiroshima > where the president's agenda will be marked by cultural and commemorative commitments. On all, the memory of the Hiroshima nuclear bombing 80 years after the tragedy during visits to the Memorial, the Museum of Peace and the association of survivors, awarded last year of the Nobel Peace Prize. It will be further moments of important exchanges that, presumably, will also leave room for a political reflection on the present and the current crisis at a global level.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Mattarella&nbsp; will therefore face a challenging journey, 16 years after the last transfer of an Italian Head of State (Giorgio Napolitano) in Japan, which takes place at a time when bilateral relations between the two countries - also thanks to the missions of 2023 of the Minister for Enterprises Adolfo Urso and the premier Giorgia&nbsp;Meloni&nbsp;- enjoy excellent Italy and Japan, the fourth world economy for nominal GDP (behind USA, China and Germany)> have seen their economic relations in constant and progressive growth, thanks to the strong interest of the Japanese for Made in Italy, especially when it rhymes with fashion, design and luxury in general.
To drag the Italian exports to the country of the Levant is also the sector of the agri-food, with the chemical-pharmaceutical and the machinery > that are increasingly affirming as a flagship compartment. If Japan, a country with high technological and manufacturing development, today has become a strategic market for Italy (which is one of its first suppliers countries) it owes itself to its position in the Indo-Pacific region, a crucial region for global balances, but also to the economic partnership agreement (Epa) in force since 2019, which has eliminated duties on about 90% of EU exports, giving a strong boost to trade flows.
At the dawn of a probable new trade war that, investing China, will force all other Asian economies, the mission of the chief of Quirinale will presumably aim to consolidate from a strategic point of view the bilateral relations between two countries that share - beyond the values of liberal democracy - the vocation for export, innovation and sustainable development. > Two countries whose future will depend on the ability to navigate demographic, productive and security challenges in the background of an increasingly unstable global scenario.
